<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3769&amp;p=29413#p29413</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3769&amp;p=29413#p29413"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Emulator colors]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3769&amp;p=29413#p29413"><![CDATA[
I wouldn't recommend using just a palette to see how it would look, since there are lots of color mixing effects you get with NTSC composite video, some making things look awful. Some emulator authors aren't interested in what happens to the pixels once they get converted into composite video, so you have to use a different emulator like Nestopia.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />That's just because the TV's pixel ratio is 3:4 when what's being displayed on screen is supposed to be 7:8(224:256), right?<br /></div><br />No, the TV screen is 4:3, but the pixels on it depend on the system generating them. To summarize, an NTSC NES pixel is about 15% wider than it is tall, and a PAL NES pixel is about 39% wider than it is tall (<a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?p=24815#24815" class="postlink">full details</a>).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Wed Dec 12, 2007 4:01 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
